ingstoke, Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1360–":"about 1360–Deceased","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1352–1407":"1352–1407","1380–1407":"1380–1407","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","about 1360":"about 1360","about 1390":"about 1390","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1360":"1360","before 1380":"before 1380","1380":"1380","1407":"1407","1390":"1390","Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Basingstoke, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carpenter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southern): occupational name for a worker in wood, Norman French <i>carpentier</i> (from Late Latin <i>carpentarius</i> ‘cartwright’).","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Zimmermann  , French   Charpentier  , Italian   Carpentieri  , or cognates and equivalents in various other languages."],"variants":[{"name":"Zimmermann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Erwin, Hans, Fritz, Gerhard, Hermann, Klaus, Gerd, Manfred, Wolfgang, Bernhard.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for a carpenter, Middle High German <i>zimberman</i> (a compound of <i>zimber</i>, <i>zim(m)er</i> ‘timber, wood’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’), German <i>Zimmermann</i>."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Carpenter was born about 1360 as the daughter of Carpenter and Emma Archmore. She married Thomas Warrener before 1380, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1360–":"umbes 1360–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1352–1407":"1352–1407","1380–1407":"1380–1407","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","about 1360":"umbes 1360","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1360":"1360","before 1380":"enne 1380","1380":"1380","1407":"1407","1390":"1390","Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Basingstoke, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1360–":"noin 1360–Kuollut","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1352–1407":"1352–1407","1380–1407":"1380–1407","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","about 1360":"noin 1360","about 1390":"noin 1390","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1360":"1360","before 1380":"ennen vuotta 1380","1380":"1380","1407":"1407","1390":"1390","Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Basingstoke, Hampshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1360–":"environ 1360–Décédée","1360–Female":"1360–Décédée","1352–1407":"1352–1407","1380–1407":"1380–1407","1390–Male":"1390–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1330–Female":"1330–Décédée","about 1360":"environ 1360","about 1390":"environ 1390","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1360":"1360","before 1380":"avant 1380","1380":"1380","1407":"1407","1390":"1390","Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Basingstoke, Hampshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Joan Carpenter est née environ 1360, fille d